{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 2.87** (also known as Manu 2.87) states that a Brahmana can attain perfection through recitation (*japa*, or mantra-recitation) alone, irrespective of performing other rites, provided he is benevolent toward all beings.[^1]\n\nThis verse concludes a passage extolling *japa* as the supreme spiritual practice. The preceding verses emphasize its superiority: the \"sacrifice of recitation\" surpasses ritual *yajña* tenfold, whispered recitation is a hundred times better, mental recitation a thousand times superior (2.85), and even the five great sacrifices pale in comparison to the *japa-yajña* (2.86).[^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-fc9632).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [passage](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-608007-p-fc9632).",
